and again.";i:17;s:15:"To know why it.";i:18;s:256:"Probably the most common phone call we get in the service department is My garage door keeps reversing and I cant get it to close or My remotes wont close the door and I have to hold the wall button until the door is all the way down for it to stay closed.";i:19;s:67:"Usually this is a sure sign that there is an issue with the garage.";i:20;s:113:"When I use the remote or wall button to close my garage door as soon as it hits the ground it goes right back up.";i:21;s:103:"To get it to stay down once it hits the ground I push the button on the remote again and it stays down.";i:22;s:140:"Turn the down limit switch screw clockwise one turn with a flat blade screwdriver if the garage door closes and then begins to open back up.";i:23;s:112:"The garage door will automatically go in reverse whenever it hits an obstruction such as the driveway or ground.";i:24;s:219:"If the door only does this with the remote and you need to hold the wall switch button continuously to bring the door down then there could be a problem with the safety sensors near the bottom of the garage door itself.";i:25;s:94:"Again the opener would see a problem there as a potential safety concern and re-open the door.";i:26;s:108:"Every garage door opener has a limit switch that controls where the door stops when it is lowered or raised.";i:27;s:172:"If your garage door wont close all the way and keeps going back up you may need to check the settings of your limit switchYou will need a flathead screwdriver to adjust it.";i:28;s:183:"Incorrect travel settings When your garage door is installed the opener is programmed with a number that indicates how far down the door is expected to travel before its fully closed.";i:29;s:167:"If the door closes before that set distance has been completed then the opener thinks theres an error and automatically reverses to prevent property damages or injury.";i:30;s:111:"When the door is in any position other than closed and the garage door opener is activated the door will close.";i:31;s:144:"If the garage door makes contact with an obstruction while closing the door will reverse the opener will beep and the lights will flash 5 times.";i:32;s:53:"ALWAYS keep remote controls out of reach of children.";i:33;s:38:"My garage door wont close all the way.";i:34;s:46:"It goes part of the way down and then back up.";i:35;s:104:"Sometimes it doesnt go down much at all and sometimes it goes almost half way down before going back up.";i:36;s:80:"There is nothing between the sensors that would cause it to trigger then sensor.";i:37;s:140:"Turn the down limit switch screw clockwise one turn with a flat blade screwdriver if the garage door closes and then begins to open back up.";i:38;s:49:"The garage door will automatically go in reverse.";i:39;s:93:"Garage door with Liftmaster opener going up and down by using the remote and the wall button.";i:40;s:45:"Garage Door Reverses when opening or closing.";i:41;s:174:"If your garage door reverses anytime you open or close it there could be a problem with your safety sensor incorrect force settings or there is an obstruction on the doorway.";i:42;s:68:"Garage door goes down but does not stay down it comes right back up.";i:43;s:161:"I tried to make adjustment from the back - Answered by a verified Home Improvement Expert We use cookies to give you the best possible experience on our website.";i:44;s:93:"To be honest it is usually one of those things thats best left to your garage door repairman.";i:45;s:62:"My garage door closes most of the way then goes back up again.";i:46;s:94:"On Sectional doors-The most common reason I see for this situation is binding torsion springs.";i:47;s:114:"If you havent had your door properly serviced in a long time than your springs may have a buildup of surface rust.";i:48;s:62:"Check the motor housing mounted to the ceiling of your garage.";i:49;s:91:"You should find two plastic screw heads or knobs on the back side or bottom of the housing.";i:50;s:88:"Start by rotating the down limit screw or knob one complete turn in the minus direction.";i:51;s:47:"Test the garage door to see if it stays closed.";i:52;s:62:"Most garage door openers have an open and close limit control.";i:53;s:107:"They are usually on the motor housing and you access them by opening a panel or removing the housing cover.";i:54;s:140:"If the door stops short of closing lengthen the close limit by turning the control knob in the direction indicated usually counterclockwise.";}}